the ego-node feature, the raw input node features are fed into a Dropout layer. In the aggregated neighborhood 
feature extraction, we reuse the intermediate results of different hops of neighbors to simplify the computation. 
For example, when computing? i Hego, we use the dot product of? ? (? i?1 Hego) instead of computing the 
power of?. Moreover, because? i?1 Hego has the same shape of Hego, computing? ? (? i?1 Hego) is always a 
sparse-dense matrix multiplication, which is more efficient than computing the power of?. Similarly, we use 
the same strategy to compute Hstrc. Because we use the original adjacency matrix instead of a normalized one in 
structure feature extraction (for accuracy performance purposes), the magnitude of A j will grow exponentially 
with j increasing, which may cause the value out of range problem. Therefore, we utilize Batch Normalization 
layers to scale down the feature matrix after each adjacency matrix multiplication. In the feature fusion module, 
we dropout the fused features before activating it with ReLU.
